Simple data reading and analysis functionalities

Anton Antonov

November 2016

Introduction

This document illustrates the use of base R functions for data reading and rudimentary data analysis.

Data summary

We see that the resulting data frame does not have the column Survival because the data frame titanic_test does not have it. Since we want to work with the survival data we are going to ignore titanic_test below.

(In general, in R very often package creators take decisions that produce incomplete or unintuitive functionality and data. Those decisions are often undocumented or hard to understand.)

Mosaic plots

Using a mosaic plot we can get (quickly) an impression of the co-dependencies of the categorical variables in a dataset. We can get better looking results using mosaic of the package vcd instead of the base function mosaicplot.

## mosaicplot( Survived ~ Sex + Pclass, titanic_train )
library(vcd)
## Loading required package: grid
mosaic( Survived ~ Sex + Pclass, titanic_train )

Contingency values

Given the Titanic passengers data let us find the average age of the passengers in each combination of values of the variables Sex and Survival.

  1. First we find the passenger counts:
pCountsDF <- xtabs( ~ Sex + Pclass, titanic_train )
pCountsDF
##         Pclass
## Sex        1   2   3
##   female  94  76 144
##   male   122 108 347
  1. Then we find the total of passenger ages:
pTotalAgesDF <- xtabs( Age ~ Sex + Pclass, titanic_train )
pTotalAgesDF
##         Pclass
## Sex            1       2       3
##   female 2942.00 2125.50 2218.50
##   male   4169.42 3043.33 6706.42
  1. Finally we divide the total ages data frame by the counts data frame:
pTotalAgesDF / pCountsDF
##         Pclass
## Sex             1        2        3
##   female 31.29787 27.96711 15.40625
##   male   34.17557 28.17898 19.32686

Distributions plots

It is a good idea to get an impression of the numerical variables distributions in a given dataset.

There are several approaches for doing this (in R and in general.)

Using base functions

First we can simply use the base function boxplot, e.g. boxplot( attitude ). In the command below the function boxplot rotates and prints all column names by the argument las=2 and uses alternating coloring by the argument col=....

boxplot( attitude, las=2, col = c("royalblue1","royalblue4") )

Alternatively, we can plot a histograms for all numerical columns.

Using the package lattice

library(lattice)
histogram( ~ values | ind, stack(attitude) )

Using the package ggplot2

Let us get fencier. Note that is this a much harder to specify plot compared to the one made with lattice above.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(stack(attitude)) + aes( x = values, fill = ind ) + 
  geom_histogram( aes(y = ..density..), binwidth=10, alpha = 0.3) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0,linetype=3) + 
  facet_grid( . ~ ind)

Cross correllations plots

It useful to visualize scatter plots made by pairs of numerical variables in a dataset. This can be easily (readily) done with the function pairs:

pairs(attitude)

Prettier and more informative plots can be obtained with other, non-base package functions.

Using the package GGally based on ggplot2

library(GGally)
ggpairs(attitude)

For more details and related plots see ggcorr: correlation matrixes with ggplot2.
